### Process collections of data asynchronously using Promises (Anti-pattern)

Source: https://github.com/pauljphilp/effectpatterns/blob/main/content/published/process-a-collection-of-data-asynchronously.mdx

This example shows a common but problematic approach using `Promise.all` to handle multiple asynchronous operations. It immediately executes all promises in parallel without concurrency limits and lacks the resource safety, structured concurrency, and composability benefits provided by Effect's `Stream` API. This can lead to unmanaged resource usage and potential errors.

```javascript
// A mock function that returns a Promise
const getUserByIdAsPromise = (id: number): Promise<{ id: number; name: string }> =>
  new Promise((resolve) => {
    setTimeout(() => {
      console.log(`Fetched user ${id}`);
      resolve({ id, name: `User ${id}` });
    }, 100);
  });

// The Promise-based program
const ids = [1, 2, 3, 4, 5];
const promises = ids.map(getUserByIdAsPromise);

Promise.all(promises).then((users) => {
  console.log('All users fetched:', users);
});
```

